The private schools in Scotland maintain a history of academic excellence, and this continued in 2018 with another collection of outstanding results in the exams, which is only reinforced by individual and collective success in sports, art, music and other community subjects.
With more than 30,000 students across Scotland, these schools, represented by the Scottish Council of Private Schools (SCIS), strive to offer the highest level to students and their parents.
Private schools aim to prepare their students for higher education, for their chosen career and their place as citizens of the world.
As an educational sector that can design and implement a tailor-made curriculum, we are seeing that modern languages continue to be a popular and desired theme within schools.
Nelson Mandela said, "If you talk to a man in a language that he understands, he knocks it over his head.
But if you speak to him in his own language, he'll reach his heart."
This is a powerful reminder that we cannot depend solely on English when we want to establish relationships and trust with people from other countries.
From the results of recent exams this year, we can see that languages are at the top of the board and at the highest approved rates in private schools.
About 68% of students who studied foreign languages got an outstanding one.
The data, compiled from the 74 schools that make up SCIS, shows that 72% of students obtained an honorary registration in Mandarin, while 72% of those who studied German, 69% of those who studied French and 63% of them who studied Spanish, also achieved an outstanding one.
This shows that Scottish private schools support languages and consider them key skills that children and young people will no doubt need in the future.
At present, languages are having the same consideration as subjects such as science, technology, engineering and mathematics in private and all kinds of school programs.
A survey carried out by the United Kingdom Employment and Training Commission in 2014 indicated that among the lack of knowledge of languages is 17% of the reasons why employers are charged with filling their vacancies.
Thus, language skills are increasingly needed to prepare youth for future careers.
These abilities are essential in a globalized world, as there are more job opportunities that need languages.
Regardless of the career you choose, if you learn a second language, you will have a real advantage in the future with a life skills like this.
Being able to communicate directly with people from other countries will put a bilingual person directly at the head of the competition.
According to a YouGov survey of more than 4,000 British adults in 2013, 75% didn't speak any foreign language well enough to maintain a conversation, and the French was the only language spoken by a two-digit percentage, in this case 15%.
That's why it's so important to invest in a language for children today.
Knowing a number of languages, especially those of developing economies, gives children more opportunities to find meaningful employment.
In Scotland, the teaching languages differ according to school.
Some schools focus on the most classic modern languages, while others are based on languages considered most important for the United Kingdom by 2020, such as Mandarin or Japanese.
Regardless of what their children's interests are, private schools always have several languages to choose and specialized teachers in this field.
Scottish private schools specialize in providing a learning environment that prepares children and teams with the skills needed to succeed, whatever the future tells them.
We cannot deny that at this time, in a global business environment, languages remain of vital importance to the future of the country, so this must be reflected in education.
