A new research that is being carried out on a highlands farm in Scotland aims to reveal how bats use the landscape to seek food.
The results are expected to shed light on the behavior of these unique flying mammals and help guide future conservation activities.
This study led by scientists of the National Trust for Scotland will follow the bats Pipstrellus pygmaeus and Pipstrellus pipstrellus, as well as the bats Myotis daubentoniii and Plecotus auritus in the gardens of Invewe in Western Ross.
Special recording equipment will be placed in key locations around the property to track bat activities during the season.
NHS staff and volunteers will also conduct mobile surveys with manual detectors.
An analysis of the sound performed by experts from all recordings will determine the frequency of the bat calls and what each species is doing.
Then a habitat map will be developed to create a detailed image at the scale of the landscape of its behavior.
Rob Dewar, NTS Nature Conservation Advisor, hopes that the results show that habitat areas are more important to bats and how they are used by each species.
This information will help determine the benefits of habitat management work, such as grassland creation and what is the best way to maintain forests for bats and other associated species.
The population of bats in Scotland and throughout the United Kingdom declined considerably in the last century.
These animals are threatened by construction and development works that affect children and the loss of habitat.
Aerogenerators and lighting also pose a risk, as well as traps with flies glue, some chemical treatments of building materials and domestic cat attacks.
The bats are not blind,
but because of his night hunting habits, his ears are more useful than his eyes in hunting.
They use a sophisticated eco-location technique to locate insects and obstacles in their flight path.
The NTS, which is responsible for the care of more than 270 historic buildings, 38 gardens and 76,000 hectares of land across the country, takes bats very seriously.
It has ten trained experts, who carry out periodic surveys, child inspections and, on occasion, even rescues.
The organization also has the only and first reserve of Scottish bats in Thrave Estate in Dumfries and Galloway, which is the home of eight of the ten species of Scottish bats.
David Thompson, Estate Manager, says this is the ideal territory for them.
"In Thrave we have a large area for bats," he says.
"We count on old buildings, historic trees and a great habitat.
But there are many things we don't know about bats yet, so the work we do here and in other properties will help us understand better what they need to prosper."
Stresses the importance of controlling the presence of bats before performing maintenance tasks in the properties, since it is possible that the involuntary destruction of a single maternity child can kill up to 400 females and young children, which could exterminate a whole local population.
The bats are a protected species and it is illegal to kill them, harass them or disturb them, as well as destroy their children.
Elisabeth Ferrell, Scottish officer of the organization Bat Conservation Trust, encourages people to help:
"There's still a lot left to learn about bats and, in the case of many species, we don't know how they're going to their populations."
