Information about the red tide: Concentrations are decreasing in Pinellas, Manatee and Sarasota
According to the latest report by the Florida Wildlife and Fisheries Commission, there is a general reduction in red tide concentrations in parts of the Tampa Bay area.
According to the aforementioned commission, they are observing increasingly unequal flowering conditions in the areas of Pinellas, Manatee, Sarasota, Charlotte and Collier counties, which may mean that concentrations are being reduced.
The red tide extends approximately 210 km from the northern counties of Pinellas to the south of Lee.
Concentrations can be found 16 km away from the Hillsborough shoreline, but in less places than last week.
The red tide was also found in Easter County.
The presence of concentrations of medium-level on the coast or away from the coast of Pinellas County was reported last week, concentrations of background and elevated away from the coast of Hillsborough County, concentrations of background and elevated in or away from the coast of Sarasota County, concentrations of background and medium-level in Charlotte County, concentrations of background and elevated in or away from the coast of Lee County, and low concentrations in Collier County.
In the counties of Pinellas, Manatee, Sarasota, Lee and Collier, there are still cases of respiratory irritation.
No such case was reported in the northwest of Florida last week.
